900604-0154.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Let America Beware
   Economic Imperialism
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   As a former journalist who covered the semiconductor area
of the electronics industry, I especially appreciated your
May 4 page-one feature "Partnership in Peril" about John
Hall's experiences with Japanese businessmen.
   In the late 1960s a strong consensus concluded that the
Japanese semiconductor capabilities were so comparatively
crude that their best hopes for catch-up (technological
parity and commercial success) rested on acquisition or
theft. After Mr. Hall, the Japanese suddenly possessed strong
capabilities.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   We underestimated Japan's determination in chips, cars,
consumer appliances and more. Many of us knew the danger of
Soviet political infiltration, but did not see Japan's
economic infiltration.
   We have no evidence that the Japanese have any sense of
business integrity that extends to the rest of the world,
that their "word" in deals or agreements is credible, or that
they practice free enterprise as a two-way street.
   I fear that the opening of Japan's markets will be even
narrower than the opening of Russia's and that we will have
to wake up to the serious risks from a Japan that cannot be
trusted, that is supremist and economically imperialistic.
   Mark B. Leeds
   New York
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0153
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0153.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   First Executive's Chairman
   To Testify for House Panel
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   FEXC
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
INSURANCE (INS)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- First Executive Corp.'s chairman and chief
executive, Fred Carr, has agreed to testify before the House
oversight and investigations subcommittee about insurance and
junk bonds.
   The subcommittee also is expected to subpoena attorneys
and accountants whom investigators have connected with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. partnerships, according to individuals
close to the panel. Those partnerships, made up mostly of
Drexel employees, invested in a number of Drexel deals and
have been the subject of subcommittee investigations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We want to establish how big these partnerships were, how
much money was going through them," said one subcommittee
official. The panel also is eager to learn what investments
were made through the partnerships as well as whether there
were misdeeds involving Drexel offerings and other
investments.
   The subcommittee already plans to offer immunity to former
Drexel junk-bond chief Michael Milken in exchange for his
testimony on the high-yield securities.
   Mr. Carr's testimony, set for June 18, will focus on the
insurance industry, in which First Executive is a sizable
player, as well as practices in the junk-bond industry. First
Executive was a major investor in junk bonds.
   A spokesman for Mr. Carr said the executive "wants to talk
about how he has managed to maintain the strong capital
position in the industry nothwithstanding his junk-bond
holdings." On Mr. Carr's relationship with Mr. Milken, the
spokesman said, "He did business with Milken, but he did
business with a lot of people."
</TEXT>
