<HL>
   Illinois Power May Have to Suspend
   Dividends on Preferred, Official Says
   ----
   By Jeffrey Taylor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9B
</SO>
<CO>
   IPC
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   DECATUR, Ill. -- Illinois Power Co. may have to suspend
payment of dividends to holders of its preferred stock.
   "I cannot say with certainty whether we will able to pay
the preferred dividend," Larry Haab, president and chief
financial officer of the electricity and natural gas concern,
conceded in an interview. "There is the potential for a legal
interpretation that when retained earnings are negative, we
cannot pay a dividend."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Power, which already has eliminated common stock
dividends, is awaiting the outcome of a rate case pending
before the Illinois Commerce Commission. The regulator's
ruling, viewed as critical to the utility's short-term
financial health, is expected Wednesday. The company had
about $474 million face value of preferred stock outstanding,
as of May 23, according to Moody's Investors Service Inc.
   On May 23, Moody's changed the direction of its review of
its rating on Illinois Power's preferred stock to "down" from
"uncertain." The rating concern cited an unfavorable
preliminary rate-order proposal from a hearing examiner in
the state commerce agency's case, a delay in a pending court
case on a previous agency order, and lower-than-anticipated
corporate earnings.
   The pivotal issue in the current commerce commission case
is whether the regulators will declare Illinois Power's
Clinton nuclear power plant 100% "used and useful," Mr. Haab
said. State regulations restrict utilities to billing
customers for only as much of a plant's cost as is necessary
to meet the overall demand for power.
   The seven-member commission ruled in March 1989 that only
27% of the plant was needed. Four members of the commission
have been replaced since then; how they intend to vote on the
Clinton issue isn't clear.
   "It is vital to us to get it (the Clinton plant) declared
`used and useful,' even if it's not incorporated into rates
in one shot," Mr. Haab said. "There is a possibility of
having to write off that portion of Clinton which is not
declared `used and useful.'"
   As of March 31, Illinois Power's retained earnings were
listed at $120.7 million. If retained earnings become
negative through a write-off, both the Federal Power Act and
the Illinois Public Utility Act stipulate interruption of
preferred stock dividends.
   In November, the state commerce commission's staff
recommended that the Clinton plant be declared 100% "used and
useful," and that Illinois Power be granted $147 million of
its $215 million rate-increase request. The agency's hearing
examiner, who acts as a judge, later recommended that Clinton
be declared 42% "used and useful," and proposed a far smaller
rate increase of $27 million.
   "My prediction is that what they'll get will be somewhere
between the staff's recommendation and the hearing
examiner's," Barry Abramson, an analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., said.
   Illinois Power's problems trace back to the commerce
commission's March 1989 refusal to allow the utility to use
100% of the Clinton plant. In the order, the commission also
said Illinois Power imprudently spent $666 million too much
on the plant. Following the 1989 order, the company took a
$346 million write-off.
   At the time, analysts said, the commission's membership
was strongly consumer-oriented. With four new members on the
commission this year, Mr. Haab hopes for a ruling more
favorable for the utility.
   Meanwhile, Illinois Power is awaiting the result of the
lawsuit it filed, challenging the 1989 order. The case is in
Illinois's Third District Appellate Court, and a ruling is
expected this fall.
   "The critical thing is that the appellate ruling be in our
favor," Mr. Haab said. "If we get a favorable decision from
the appellate court, there will be no write-off this year."
   Such an outcome is unlikely, Mr. Abramson, the
Prudential-Bache analyst, said.
   The court is expected to rule both on whether the utility
can use all of the Clinton plant and on whether it spent too
much money to build it.
   "I don't see any scenario under which they're not going to
have to write off $248 million, after tax, for imprudent
spending," Mr. Abramson said. "Based on that assumption,
they'd have a negative retained income, which would preclude
them from paying preferred dividends for a time."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0142
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0142.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Wal-Mart's Walton Predicts Company
   Could Quintuple Sales by the Year 2000
   ----
   By Robert Tomsho
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9C
</SO>
<CO>
   WMT
</CO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. -- Saying he views his
multibillion-dollar retail empire as "just a small regional
company," Wal-Mart Stores Inc. Chairman Sam M. Walton said he
thought the company could quintuple sales to about $125
billion by the year 2000.
   Last year, Wal-Mart's earnings increased 29% to $1 billion
on sales of $25.8 billion. If achieved, Mr. Walton's goals
for the end of the decade would boost the discount retailer
into the same league with corporate giants like General
Motors Corp., whose 1989 revenue was $126.9 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I really believe it's possible," Wal-Mart's 72-year-old
founder said at the annual meeting as he stood at the end of
a lighted walkway that extended into the middle of a
University of Arkansas sports arena. Though treated for a
form of cancer of the blood and bones earlier in the year,
the Arkansas billionaire had the fire and vigor of a revival
preacher as he led more than 8,000 shareholders and employees
in a series of call-and-response cheers.
   "Can we do it?" he shouted.
   "Yes we can," they roared back.
   Mr. Walton predicted the company would double the number
of Wal-Mart and Sam's Wholesale Club stores, increase both
their average size and annual sales and continue to expand
outside the company's traditional base in the South and
Midwest.
   By the end of the decade, he said he expects the number of
Wal-Mart stores to climb to about 3,000 from about 1,400 now
and their average size increase to about 80,000 square feet
from about 66,400 square feet. He predicted that Wal-Mart
store total sales would climb to about $96 billion annually
from about $21 billion last year and that per-square foot
sales would jump to $400 annually from about $250 last year.
   While talking little about the disappointing results at
the corporation's four huge Hypermart U.S.A. outlets, Mr.
Walton said he hoped that Sam's Wholesale Club outlets would
increase in number to about 300 from 127 and that Sam's
annual revenue would increase to about $30 billion from about
$4.8 billion last year.
   "It all rides on our people," said Mr. Walton, who added
that although Wal-Mart is "getting to be a large company, we
have to act small and move quickly."
   William W. Whyte, an analyst with Stephens Inc. in Little
Rock, Ark., said WalMart, which concentrates its operations
in small towns, could probably double its number of outlets
just by moving into new markets in the 28 states where it
already has operations.
   Noting innovations such as the company's recent efforts to
add discount grocery operations to some of its Wal-Mart
outlets, Mr. Whyte added that he would not be surprised if
Wal-Mart achieved the lofty goals laid out by its chairman
and founder. "They never cease to amaze me," he said. "With
them, we just take it one quarter at a time."
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday,
Wal-Mart jumped $2 to $58.375.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0141
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0141.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Markets:
   Tokyo Stocks Fall Slightly on Profit-Taking,
   While London Gains on Takeover Speculation
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST JAPAN EUROP CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tokyo stock prices finished lower in moderate trading
Friday after posting gains in the two previous days.
   Meanwhile, London share prices peaked at the close of
moderate trading, tracking Wall Street's firming and scoring
late-day gains on unconfirmed rumors of a takeover bid in the
brewery sector.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Investors in Japan took profits ahead of the weekend on
domestic demand-related shares, many of which advanced
strongly earlier last week, traders said. Construction
companies were broadly lower. Shipbuilding and steel issues
also declined, while some electrical and mining shares
firmed.
   The Nikkei index of 225 selected issues closed down 239.68
points at 32891.12. The index advanced 204.54 points
Thursday.
   At mid-morning in Tokyo Monday, the Nikkei index was up
85.88 points to 32977.
   Friday's volume on the first section was estimated at 700
million shares, down from 805 million shares Thursday.
   Declining issues Friday outnumbered advancing issues 541
to 426, while 152 issues remained unchanged.
   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed in the
first section, which gained 18.65 points Thursday, was down
9.19 points, or 0.38%, at 2426.55.
   The second section index, which advanced 35.96 points
Thursday, was up 36.34 points, or 0.91%, to close at 3974.62.
Volume in the second section was estimated at 29 million
shares, up from 18 million shares Thursday.
   Stock prices moved lower in the afternoon. Traders said
investors decided to secure profits on stocks that advanced
in the past few days ahead of the announcement of U.S.
employment data later Friday. The figures, along with the
U.S.-Soviet summit talks in Washington over the weekend, were
expected to affect the direction of exchange rates.
   While they took profits on construction and shipbuilding
shares, investors actively hunted for speculative shares as
well as individual stocks with strong earnings outlooks,
traders said.
   "The market mood was bullish. Investors showed strong
interest searching for stocks with high potential to
advance," said Masami Okuma, a senior trader at UBS Phillips
&amp; Drew International.
   Main buyers last week were individuals and corporate
investors, while most institutional investors took profits on
the recovery in stock prices, said Atsushi Koishihara,
general manager of stock trading at Taiheiyo Securities.
   Active selling by institutional investors in previous
weeks helped reduce selling pressure and made stock prices
resistant to sharp falls, Mr. Okuma of UBS Phillips said.
   The market is expected to firm this week because brokerage
houses are planning to trade actively as they usually do in
the first part of a month, according to some traders.
   In London, the rumors of a brewery takeover bid
precipitated heavy buying in the sector, particularly for
Allied-Lyons shares, as speculation mounted that it was the
focus of a predator. The rumors were unsubstantiated.
   In addition, strong stock futures trading lent support to
shares, as did the continued shortage of stock in the hands
of marketmakers and rumors of a cut in U.S. prime lending
rates.
   The combined effect of these factors sent dealers home
convinced that this week will see robust trading.
   "We'll break through 2400 {on the Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100 Share Index}" early this week, predicted one
trader.
   At the close of Friday trading, the 100 Share Index was up
26.3 points at 2371.4. Its low of the day was reached early
in the session, when the index fell 12.4 points.
   The narrower Financial Times 30 Share Index was up 27.4
points at 1882.4. Volume was 499.3 million shares, above the
466.2 million issues that changed hands Thursday.
   In the futures markets, the June FT-SE 100 index contract
ended trading at 2411.0, up from its close of 2379.0
Thursday. Similarly, dealers expected Wall Street to perform
strongly this week.
   Allied-Lyons rose 26 pence to 500 ($8.42) on the rumors.
However, company spokesmen couldn't be reached to comment.
   The entire brewery sector profited from the speculation,
particularly as marketmakers were short of stock in the
sector, following Thursday's brisk buy activity in Guinness
shares. Bass gained 20 pence to #11.04. Guinness gained a
further seven pence to 776.
   Other shares performing well Friday included Rothmans,
which said it was considering the acquisition of the
Theodorus Niemeyer BV group of companies from Gallaher Ltd.,
a wholly owned subsidiary of American Brands Inc.
   One trader said the market took the news well and assumed
that this would signal Rothmans' exit from South African
markets. Rothmans gained 39 pence to 732.
   Shares that fell included Rank, which fell 15 pence to 803
on news that it had bid #512 million ($860.7 million) for
Mecca Leisure.
   Elsewhere, share prices closed higher in Frankfurt,
Zurich, Brussels, Amsterdam, Stockholm and Milan. Shares were
lower in Paris, and South African gold stocks closed down.
   Prices closed higher in Sydney, Hong Kong, Singapore,
Seoul and Taipei. They were mixed in Wellington and Manila.
                                                                                                       

