900604-0125.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Workplace (A Special Report): Higher Tech
   ---
   Seat of Power:
   The Most Important Piece of Equipment
   In the Office Remains Steadfastly Low-Tech
   ----
   By James S. Hirsch
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE R21
</SO>
<IN>
OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)
</IN>
<LP>
   STODGY OR STATELY, lacquered or leather-bound, the office
chair has always been much more than a place to sit. It
projects power. It reflects the technological revolution of
the workplace. And it's there when you need it.
   "Everything in the office seems to distance you from human
contact, like the panels, phones and computers, so the chair
becomes an island, something personal," says Scott Star,
group product director at Knoll International, a furniture
maker. "My secretary took my chair when I was on vacation,
and when I came back I felt invaded."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Today's agile office chair -- tilting and twisting like a
Texas two-stepper -- is a far cry from the bulky executive
armchairs used in the mid-19th century. These creations, with
high stiff backs and embroidered cushions, looked impressive
but were soon unsuitable for the changing workplace. By the
end of the century, the typewriter had moved into the office,
and that required a new kind of chair. Primarily for women
who worked as secretaries, the "task chair" was armless,
mounted on wheels and had a low, adjustable back.
   Thus began a caste system that held sway for many years.
Underlings who toiled all day on typewriters, on adding
machines and at telephone switchboards sat in smaller,
functional chairs; bigwigs who made decisions but never
dirtied their fingernails got the overstuffed, leatherbound
thrones.
   "The large executive chair elevates the sitter," Emilio
Ambasz, a New York architect and industrial designer, once
said. "It distances him. It protects the body. There is a
tall back to rest {his head}, and it is covered with the skin
of some animal, preferably your predecessor."
   Designers say that nothing is more difficult than making a
chair, it being so small and people being so long. Sitting,
according to this theory, is an unnatural position because it
applies pressure on the spine. Humans, it seems, are much
better off lying down or standing up.
   The chair, though, has not lacked innovation. In the 1920s
and '30s, the German Bauhaus design movement inspired all
sorts of spare, no-nonsense tubular-steel office chairs whose
emphasis was on style and mass production. After World War
II, sitting improved with Charles Eames's molded plywood and
fiberglass chairs, whose contoured and shell-shaped chairs
conformed more naturally to the body.
   By the 1970s, the two-tier chair system began to crumble
as a new movement emerged called "ergonomics." The word
simply means the relationship between people and work.
Applied to chairs, it refers to seats that adjust, bend or
pivot in ways that are both functional and comfortable.
   Giving high-quality chairs to all levels of workers
highlights how technology has transformed the workplace and
how the desk has been replaced by the work station. No longer
is "machine work" consigned to secretaries. Now middle- and
top-level managers, as well as their subordinates, write on
video display terminals, process data, punch Quotron machines
and work with high-tech gadgets. That means almost everyone
needs a nimble, high-performance chair, a task chair for the
information age.
   Thronelike executive chairs are also going by the wayside
as women move up the ranks. "They don't like the fat-cat
look," says John Berry, a spokesman for Herman Miller Inc.,
an office-furniture maker in Zeeland, Mich.
   The top brass, however, still want chairs with status, so
furniture makers are rolling out lines of chairs similar in
style but tailored differently for staff workers, middle
managers and executives. The big shots, for example, love to
recline, so they get chairs with added back support.
   Some designers suspect that future office chairs will look
more like living-room furniture, which would create a better
office social environment, while others look for chairs that
will move more harmoniously with the natural movements of the
body.
   But there will never be a perfect chair. William Stumpf,
an office-furniture designer, notes that the body's ideal
position is to be floating in water, which is good news for
scuba divers and mermaids but cold comfort for the sedentary
office masses.
   ---
   Mr. Hirsch is a staff reporter in The Wall Street
Journal's Pittsburgh bureau.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0124
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0124.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Sid and Lee Bass,
   Airlie Group Sue
   Kidder Peabody
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   FEXC GE
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Interests linked to Texas investors Sid and Lee Bass have
sued Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., alleging that the securities firm
defrauded them of more than $52 million in an October 1989
rights offering by First Executive Corp.
   The litigation, filed early last month in Fort Worth
federal court, surfaced publicly only recently. It seeks
unspecified actual and punitive damages as well as recision
of the purchase of First Executive securities. At March 31,
Airlie Group held an 8.9% stake in First Executive, which
isn't named as a defendant in the suit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Kidder Peabody spokesman disputed the suit's allegations
and said "we don't think the complaint is well grounded and
expect that our view of the matter will prevail."
   The plaintiffs include two personal holding companies
bearing the brothers' names -- Sid R. Bass Inc., Lee M. Bass
Inc.; Airlie Group L.P., a limited partnership based in
Greenwich, Conn., whose general partners are investor Dort A.
Cameron III and a holding company operated by Fort Worth
investor Thomas Taylor; and Mr. Cameron individually.
   The action by the Bass brothers' interests and Airlie is
the latest of a number of suits relating to the rights
offering of First Executive, a Los Angeles-based insurance
holding company. Much of the earlier litigation has been
consolidated as a purported class action in federal court in
Los Angeles.
   The Bass brothers and Airlie allege that Kidder, a General
Electric Corp. unit described in the suit as in financial
straits last year and badly in need of the estimated $5
million in fees that would result, underwrote a $284 million
"exotic securities package" for First Executive. The package
consisted of rights units which entitled holders to buy a
package of convertible preferred stock and warrants to buy
common stock.
   The suit alleges that the prospectus related to the issue
omitted key information about First Executive. Not long after
the successful securities sale, First Executive disclosed
that its junk bond holdings were overvalued by hundreds of
millions of dollars. Insurance regulators rejected a
complicated securities transaction intended to boost legally
required reserves. And an anticipated $460 million sale of
First Executive's New York unit fell through.
   First Executive's stock price plummeted from about $12.25
a share when the rights offering was completed to as low as
$2.25 a share earlier this year.
   First Executive stock closed Friday at $2.50 a share in
over-the-counter trading. The company, noting that it isn't
named as a defendant in the latest lawsuit, declined comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0123
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0123.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Ratings:
   Ratings on Xerox's
   Debt, Preferred Stock
   Are Under Review
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   XRX
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it will consider
lowering its ratings on debt and preferred stock of Xerox
Corp. and several of its subsidiaries.
   About $2 billion of the parent company's debt is affected.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   S&amp;P said its review is a result of the possible effect of
problems at the company's Crum &amp; Forster insurance unit.
Separately, S&amp;P said it will consider lowering its rating on
Crum &amp; Forster's claims-paying ability, citing uncertainty
about the quality of the company's reinsurance arrangements
and continuing weakness in the property-casualty market.
   S&amp;P said it was concerned about Crum &amp; Forster's potential
for producing charges against Xerox's earnings, and its
possible need for capital infusions from the parent. It also
said it will review Crum &amp; Forster's ability to contribute to
dividends to Xerox, a business equipment and financial
services concern based in Stamford, Conn.
   Aside from the Crum &amp; Forster rating, which is double-A,
S&amp;P placed on its CreditWatch list: Xerox's senior debt,
rated single-A-plus; its subordinated debt, rated single-A;
its preferred stock, rated single-A-plus; Xerox Credit
Corp.'s senior debt, rated single-A-plus; and Xerox Credit
Overseas Finance NV's senior debt, rated single-A-plus.
   In a statement, Xerox said: "We are obviously disappointed
at this announcement and will meet with representatives of
Standard &amp; Poor's in the near future. Our balance sheet is
healthy and we have sound strategies in place to improve
financial performance and shareholder value."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
