<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Gorbachev, While Still a Hit Here,
   Is Dogged by Crises in Soviet Union
   ----
   By David Shribman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. -- He alighted from his Ilyushin 62 jet to
the strains of "Stars and Stripes Forever." He gestured bulky
cameramen out of his way to greet a mob of Americans,
including protesters. He charmed politicians, artists and
industrial leaders over corn cakes, Canadian walleye and
Wisconsin veal.
   Though Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev luxuriates in
his image as the pathfinder of perestroika, his trip here
yesterday to the soggy Midwestern plains and today to the
Pacific Coast and California's Silicon Valley fits
comfortably into a traditional political and diplomatic
pattern. He is only the latest in a long string of
politicians to seek political support at home through the
cheers of crowds abroad.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   And so when Mr. Gorbachev strode across fortuitously named
Summit Avenue into the governor's mansion, tooled through the
streets of the Twin Cities, and met with Midwestern farm and
business leaders in a gleaming, modern hotel, he was
following a path established when Peter the Great first
traveled West nearly three centuries ago.
   But like Peter the Great's voyages, Mr. Gorbachev's trip
is a working vacation from his troubles, with reminders every
time he passed a St. Paul supermarket -- boneless sirloins,
ready for the grill, are on sale for $2.99 a pound at
Knowlan's Market here this week -- of the food,
manufacturing, political and cultural crises that await him
when he returns tomorrow. Last week alone, he faced a
challenge from his rival Boris Yeltsin, the new president of
the Russian republic, and the threat that several regions
would refuse to send food to Moscow.
   The result is that, for all his public triumphs
barnstorming the U.S. this week, there were hints here in
Minnesota that Mr. Gorbachev is under siege in Moscow.
   "The act is getting a little bit old this time," says
Michael Sheehan, who does speech coaching and provides poise
instruction for Democratic politicians. "It's like going to a
Broadway show with the first replacement cast: It's still
being done very well, but it doesn't have the surprise and
freshness it did the first time."
   It did have bluntness, however. Mr. Gorbachev complained
about his own "military-industrial complex" and, almost
sheepishly, asked for U.S. investment, telling American
businessmen, "You won't lose your money in the Soviet Union."
The Soviet leader admitted to a roomful of committed
capitalists that "our old system became weak," adding that
"there has been some damage done to our economy."
   Mr. Gorbachev's itinerary underlined his struggles. Peter
the Great traveled West in 1697 to learn shipbuilding -- he
actually helped lay the hull of a ship -- to help imperial
Russia build a navy and boost its flagging war against the
Turks in the Crimea. Mr. Gorbachev traveled West to learn
about computers and corn yields to help boost his country's
economic base as it creates the foundation of a more
market-oriented society.
   But unlike Peter the Great, who traveled incognito, Mr.
Gorbachev and his handlers choreographed every step, even
going so far as to build in room for the spontaneity that has
become his trademark. When he abandoned his motorcade and
took to the streets outside the black iron spikes of the
governor's mansion, he defused the anger of Baltic
demonstrators who were calling for the freedom of Lithuania.
One of the protest leaders pronounced herself "excited" by
Mr. Gorbachev's gesture.
   Not least among his entourage was Oleg Uralov, who holds
the remarkable title of deputy minister of cinematography of
the U.S.S.R. and also is the chief executive officer of a
Soviet firm called Videofilm.
   "The primary goal here is to portray Gorbachev as a man,
as a human being," says Mr. Uralov, whose language is studded
with the cheerful catechism of perestroika. "Landscapes were
not the decisive factor in the intinerary."
   But the Gorbachev visit was far from that innocent. It
wasn't a coincidence, for example, that Mr. Gorbachev's aides
specifically requested that Raisa Gorbachev visit a family
with four children, a dog and working parents. Thus did
Steven and Karen Watson and their home at 4841 Garfield Ave.,
South Minneapolis, gain their shimmery moment in the
spotlight.
   The Soviets know, moreover, that the most enduring moments
of Nikita Khrushchev's visit to the U.S. in 1959 were the
glimpse of the general secretary munching a hot dog and the
sight of him picking up silage (and smelling it) on Roswell
Garst's farm in Coon Rapids, Iowa.
   "Gorbachev's people are as concerned about the `visuals'
as American advance people," says David Van Note of North
Conway, N.H., who was pressed into service here because of
his work in the Democratic presidential candidacies of John
Glenn in 1984 and Bruce Babbitt in 1988. "They know the
pictures have to convey the theme Gorbachev wants to convey
at home. He wanted the business meeting to look like a
business meeting. We're not talking about people who don't
know the value of media coverage to convey an idea."
   That doesn't mean that the campaign-style trip Mr.
Gorbachev is completing today will play in the Politburo or
even in Pinsk.
   National leaders who seek political boosts outside their
borders seldom win more than temporary blips in their
support. When Benjamin Disraeli -- his star fading, his
country beset with economic problems and his party threatened
by a rejuvenated William Gladstone -- traveled to the
Congress of Berlin in 1878, he patched up Europe for a
generation and returned home to be the first to use the
gilded phrase "peace with honor." It didn't help much.
   Richard Nixon didn't find the solace or salvation he
sought when he traveled to Egypt in June 1974, drawing huge
crowds in Cairo and Alexandria as the House Judiciary
Committee girded to vote on the articles of impeachment and
as the Supreme Court prepared to hand down an 8-0 decision
forcing the president to hand over taped conversations to the
Watergate special prosecutor. "He wanted to show he was still
respected and honored abroad," says Stephen Ambrose, a
University of New Orleans biographer of Mr. Nixon. "The trip
was designed to let it soak in that if Nixon left, we'd be
stuck with Jerry Ford."
   But Mr. Gorbachev did provide a bravura performance, at
least for domestic consumption in the U.S.
   "He's not like most of the Democrats -- he's willing to
take on Bush now and then on issues," says Frank Mankiewicz,
a former campaign adviser to the late Robert Kennedy, and
former Sens. George McGovern and Gary Hart. "And while an
American politician would have tried to hide that birthmark,
he makes a thing of it. His instincts are great."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Movies:
   Hollywood Turns to Russia, With Love
   ----
   By Kathleen A. Hughes
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   CRC TBSA FREST PCC FE
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Hollywood producers are turning Red Square into their
latest back lot, and they have the blessing of the Soviet
Union's top mogul.
   In fact, when Mikhail Gorbachev chatted with entertainment
magnate Ted Turner, actress Jane Fonda and physician Robert
Gale during a lunch at the Soviet Embassy in Washington last
week, they talked a bit about movies made in the U.S.S.R.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It was a timely subject. Last Wednesday in Moscow, Carolco
Pictures Inc. and Turner Network Television began filming
"The Final Warning," a television movie about Dr. Gale
(played by John Voight), who treated radiation victims after
the nuclear accident at Chernobyl.
   "I told Gorbachev the film was going very well," Dr. Gale
says. "Jane told him what it was like to make the first
co-production with the Soviet Union in 1976 {`The Blue
Bird'}. It's light-years of difference now. We're proceeding
without interference."
   The Soviet movie industry is changing rapidly in the wake
of glasnost and perestroika. In a bid for hard currency,
Soviet film companies have been aggressively trying to lure
more big-spending Hollywood film crews inside Soviet borders
for co-productions and other types of service agreements. And
more producers are starting to take the bait.
   Soyuzkinoservice, a Soviet film finance, production and
distribution company also known as SKS, even opened a new
office in Hollywood last year, the USSR Film Service Corp.,
as a joint venture. To make its presence known, it held gala
parties in October and February. More than 800 movie types,
including Mr. Voight and producer Paul Maslansky, went to the
latest party and were courted with vodka, caviar and blinis.
   Progress has been somewhat slow. After a year, the USSR
Film Service, headed by Soviet-born Yuri Spilny, has
negotiated or is in the process of negotiating 10 co-ventures
or service agreements for movie projects. There are two
projects on Chernobyl in the works, a TV miniseries about
Leon Trotsky, a contemporary version of "Crime and
Punishment," a movie about the Nazi siege of Leningrad and a
science-fiction project, among others.
   What are the Soviets offering? Locations such as Red
Square and the Winter Palace, a lot of extras at very low
prices, military equipment, period costumes, translators,
hard-to-get hotel reservations, Soviet production teams.
   In exchange, they typically request hard currency and
distribution rights in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
In some cases, a cut of the profit. They are also upgrading
their rental equipment, and they want to train their own film
makers in special effects.
   For "The Final Warning," SKS is providing the use of a
nuclear power plant 500 miles east of Moscow, Soviet army
troops, helicopters, equipment and crew for around $1
million. The Soviet Union will also get the distribution
rights in the U.S.S.R. and Eastern Europe.
   Co-productions between the Soviets and U.S. film makers
aren't entirely new. The Soviets set up SKS 20 years ago, and
several U.S. movies, such as "Blue Bird" and "Red Heat," have
been filmed in Russia. But before glasnost, the Soviet
bureaucracy made it difficult to get movies made. There are
legendary stories in Hollywood about films brought to a
screeching halt by KGB agents and customs officials.
   In the past two years, the largest of the Soviet Union's
39 movie studios have been decentralized and are now allowed
to negotiate deals on their own to earn some profits. So a
few are now competing with SKS to provide film services.
   "The Soviet Union is starting to look a lot like
Hollywood," says Ilmar Taska, director of Soviet projects for
Fries Entertainment. "New companies are growing like
mushrooms in the rain."
   The mostly independent producers who are starting
negotiations are wary of the uncharted territory. "It's a
whole new world with the Soviets. The rules are changing
literally as we speak," says Bob O'Connor, who is talking to
USSR Film Service about making a contemporary version of
"Crime and Punishment" in Leningrad. "You're a babe in the
woods."
   Some recent veterans say negotiating a contract in the
Soviet Union can be slow going. The Soviets also lack much of
the equipment that Hollywood producers take for granted, such
as a large number of portable toilets, dressing rooms and big
hotel suites. Just making a phone call from the Soviet Union
to the U.S. or Europe often requires a reservation and may
take hours.
   Dr. Gale says that in working on "Final Warning," he
suggested actors use an ophthalmoscope, the flashlight device
doctors use to examine eyes. "In Los Angeles we would have
had one in two seconds, but there it became a major
undertaking," he says. A number of doctors contacted didn't
have one, and when the crew found a doctor who did, he wasn't
eager to part with it for a day.
   One recently completed film, "The Russia House," a Soviet
love/spy story starring Sean Connery and Michelle Pfeiffer,
is scheduled for release by Pathe Communications Co. later
this year. Mr. Maslansky, producer of the $20 million movie,
says he negotiated the film services he needed through Corona
Film, a private company that worked with Mosfilm Studios, one
of the main Soviet studios. Mr. Maslansky says it took about
4 1/2 weeks to iron out the details of what the Soviets would
provide, and the process was "arduous and rather complex."
   He finally agreed to pay about 2.8 million rubles (in
dollars at a rate he won't disclose) in exchange for Soviet
production services, including hotel reservations,
transportation, technical personnel and some equipment. But
most of the movie equipment he needed just wasn't available
in the Soviet Union. So Mr. Maslansky brought in about 40
vehicles, including portable dressing rooms and toilets,
along with trucks for electrical equipment.
   The producer also flew in a caterer from England to survey
food supplies. The caterer concluded that "we better bring
everything in," the producer says. So Mr. Maslansky brought
in four catering trucks with enough beef, frozen vegetables
and fruit to feed 120 crew members breakfast and lunch for
about two weeks.
   Despite the physical obstacles, Mr. Maslansky describes
the Russian production team as "first rate." And he says the
filming "rates as one of the best film experiences I have
had." He also notes: "You go to the Soviet Union for the
locations. You don't go to save money. . . . It's terribly
difficult to get a movie done, but everything is possible."
   For others, negotiations within the Soviet studio system
can become confusing. Fries Entertainment agreed to make a
movie called "In Siberian Captivity" with a Soviet director;
Fries later found that the director had moved the project
from one studio to another, requiring renegotiation of
services. In addition, the director kept asking for "more and
more money." At one point, "It wasn't clear who had the
rights to the project," says Fries's Mr. Taska. Fries finally
dropped the project at the end of last year. "It wasn't a
workable situation," says Mr. Taska. Fries still plans to
produce two other movies in the Soviet Union, and Mr. Taska
says: "Generally those talks have been satisfactory. It's not
always such a problem."
   The Soviets have a more active role in actual
co-productions, such as "900 Days: The Siege of Leningrad," a
movie about the Nazi effort to take the city. Alberto
Grimaldi, a producer who negotiated through USSR Film Service
and SKS, says the Soviets are going to provide "everything
necessary to film the movie," including tanks, armies and
crowds. In exchange, the Soviets will get 40% of the net
income, plus distribution rights in Eastern Europe, India and
the U.S.S.R.
   Producers have been pleasantly surprised by the Soviet
willingness to participate in projects that might seem
controversial. Producer Josef Shaftel says he met with USSR
Film Service about making a four-hour miniseries on Trotsky.
"They flipped out over the idea," he says. Mr. Shaftel, who
made an earlier movie on Trotsky, says the Soviets agreed to
provide a Russian writer who is translating previously
undisclosed material from historical archives on Stalin,
Lenin and Trotsky.
   The Soviets are also paying for living expenses in the
Soviet Union for more than a week for a research trip for Mr.
Shaftel, his wife and a writer. "With the opening of the
archives, they are being very honest and open. It's
extraordinary," says Mr. Shaftel. "Now I have access to
material I didn't have 20 years ago."
   As Hollywood interest grows, some film executives expect
that the Soviets may become less generous in their
negotiations. "The dollar has a lot of value right now, and
the terms are affordable and interesting for Americans," says
Mr. Taska. "But as the Soviets enter the world market, their
prices may catch up. They know how much films cost in
Hollywood and France."
   ---
                  On Location In the U.S.S.R.
                                                                                                       

