<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among Friday's offerings and pricings
in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                       CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   BellSouth Savings &amp; Employee Stock Ownership Trust -- $275
million of amortizing medium-term notes, due July 1, 2003,
were priced at par to yield 9.19%. The notes were priced at a
spread of 0.70 percentage point above the Treasury's 10-year
note. Rated double-A-1 by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and
triple-A by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the non-callable issue
will be sold through underwriters led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. -- $150 million of 9.35% medium-term
notes, due June 16, 2020, was priced at 99.945 to yield
9.36%. The non-callable notes, which may be put back to the
company in the seventh year, were priced at a spread of 0.89
percentage point above the Treasury's seven-year note. Rated
single-A-3 by Moody's and single-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be
sold through Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.
   Boston Edison Co. -- $100 million of 9 7/8% debentures,
due June 1, 2020, were priced at 99.09 to yield 9.97%. The
debentures, which are non-callable for 10 years, were priced
at a spread of 1.55 percentage points above the Treasury's
30-year bond. Rated Baa-2 by Moody's and triple-B by S&amp;P, the
issue will be sold through underwriters led by Goldman Sachs.
   Commercial Credit Corp. -- $100 million of notes, due June
15, 2010, were priced at par to yield 8.70%. The non-callable
notes, which may be put back to the company in the third,
sixth, ninth, 12th and 15th years, were priced at a spread of
0.375 percentage point above the Treasury's three-year note.
Rated Baa-1 by Moody's and single-A-minus by S&amp;P, the issue
will be sold through underwriters led by Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
   International Paper Co. -- $100 million of 9.40% notes,
due June 1, 2002, was priced at 99.703 to yield 9.44%. The
non-callable notes were priced at a spread of one percentage
point above the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated single-A-3 by
Moody's and single-A-minus by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold
through underwriters led by First Boston Corp.
   Mountain States Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. -- $90 million
of 9 5/8% debentures, due June 1, 2030, were priced at 99.417
to yield 9.682%. The debentures, which are non-callable for
five years, were priced at a spread of 1.25 percentage points
above the Treasury's 30-year bond. Rated double-A-3 by
Moody's and double-A-minus by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold
through underwriters led by Morgan Stanley. Mountain States
Telephone is a unit of U S West Inc.
                                                                                                       

