<HL>
   International:
   British &amp; Commonwealth
   Is Entering `Proceedings'
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   U.BCO
</CO>
<LP>
   LONDON -- After giving up on a possible rescue package to
be worked out with creditors, troubled financial-services
concern British &amp; Commonwealth Holdings PLC agreed to "enter
administration," which is comparable to U.S. Chapter 11
bankruptcy proceedings.
   On Friday, following unsuccessful negotiations with banks,
Britain's Securities and Investment Board removed B&amp;C from
the list of financial concerns where other regulated
financial houses can place client money. The SIB, after
consulting with the Bank of England, explained in a brief
statement that it took the unusual step "as a matter of
urgency in consultation with the other regulators concerned,
in the interests of investor protection."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   British &amp; Commonwealth began to teeter in April when it
was forced to write off #550 million ($923.2 million) in
losses at its Atlantic Computers PLC unit. It placed the unit
in the hands of an independent administrator.
   Exco International PLC, a B&amp;C subsidiary acquired in late
1986, won't be part of the proceedings, but will be spun off
sometime this summer. Exco deals in money brokerage, foreign
exchange and money markets around the world. It hasn't been
affected by B&amp;C's problems and has maintained its own capital
base separate from the parent company.
   Richard Lacy, chairman of Exco, said a "management buy-out
is the most likely outcome," but he left open the possibility
the company might be merged into another financial concern."
It's expected that Exco would be acquired for about #200
million ($340 million).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing Brief -- A/S/M Communications Inc.:
   Affiliated Publications Inc.
   To Acquire an 80% Stake
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   AFP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Affiliated Publications Inc., publisher of the Boston
Globe and a stable of trade magazines, said it has agreed to
acquire 80% of A/S/M Communications Inc., publisher of Adweek
magazine.
   The purchase price was not disclosed, but industry
executives familiar with the transaction estimated the
Boston-based Affiliated paid about $17 million for the stake
to a group of private holders. Kenneth Fadner, president of
A/S/M, is the largest holder; he will continue in his post
and retain a substantial portion of the remaining 20%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Adweek, started in 1978, has been battered by a decline in
advertising by media companies. A/S/M, attempting to ease
financial difficulties, had quietly folded seven publications
in recent months, and had been seeking an outside investor to
provide cash.
   Affiliated is acquiring Adweek, Adweek's Marketing Week,
and Photo District News. All of the A/S/M titles will become
part of BPI Communications Inc, Affiliated's specialty
publishing subsidiary.
   Adweek will be a strategic addition to BPI
Communications's growing group of media and
entertainment-related magazines. BPI also publishes The
Hollywood Reporter, Billboard, Back Stage, American Film,
Photo Design and Interiors.
</TEXT>
