<HL>
   Business Brief -- Televideo Systems Inc.:
   Firm Sets Up Joint Venture
   To Sell Systems in Moscow
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   TELV FREST
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. -- Televideo Systems Inc. said it has
signed two joint-venture agreements to market the company's
computer systems in the Soviet Union.
   The agreement, which also involves West Germany's ABM
Computer Systems, will provide computers to the city of
Moscow and the Ministry of Construction. The companies will
offer computers and computer parts for resale through a
computer store chain in Moscow that will be set up as part of
the venture. Terms weren't disclosed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Televideo said it doesn't expect the venture to be
profitable for about two years. Initially, it expects to
provide 1,000 to 2,000 systems a month.
   As part of the agreement, Moscow is providing land near
the Kremlin that the joint-venture parties will develop into
a hotel and office complex for western visitors and a source
of hard currency earnings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0058
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0058.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Nashville Network:
   Radio Broadcaster to Halt
   Round-the-Clock Operations
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   WX
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Nashville Network's radio division, which delivered
around-the-clock programming via satellite emphasizing
country music, said it would cease full-time operations at
the end of the month.
   The 18-month-old service, called TNNR, will continue to
produce a weekly show that is sold through syndication. TNNR
is a joint venture of Opryland USA, a privately held company
owned by Gaylord Broadcasting Co., and Group W Satellite, a
unit of Westinghouse Electric Co.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Since the network began in December 1988, it signed only
63 affiliates. According to a spokeswoman for Group W, an
unspecified number of on-air personalities will be laid off.
   The venture cost the partners between $5 million and $10
million, said Robert Unmacht, managing editor of M Street
Journal, a Washington, D.C., publication that follows the
radio industry.
   The discontinuation of TNNR will not affect TNN, a cable
TV network, the Group W spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
