<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   DONALD TRUMP is in intense talks with bank creditors that
could force him to give up big chunks of his empire. The
bankers, concerned about the developer's critical cash
shortage, are likely to seek asset sales, new management and
a much more conservative operating style.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrials closed above 2900 for the first
time Friday as stocks and bonds surged in anticipation of
falling interest rates. The stock average rose 24.31 to
2900.97. Last week's record-setting equity prices also
reflect rising expectations for 1990 and 1991 corporate
earnings.
   ---
   Private-sector payrolls barely grew in May after shrinking
in April, the government said. But temporary census hiring
lowered the civilian unemployment rate to 5.3% from 5.4%.
Meanwhile, the purchasing managers' index of manufacturing
health rose to its highest level since April 1989.
                                                                                                       

   The soft jobs picture is leading economists to prune
forecasts of second-quarter gross national product.
   ---
   The Soviet Union is depositing large amounts of gold with
Western banks as collateral for loans. Trade creditors owed
hundreds of millions of dollars have been hounding the
cashpoor Soviets for overdue payments.
   ---
   Chevron and the Soviets agreed to study the feasibility of
jointly developing the huge Tengiz oil field. It could be the
biggest U.S.-Soviet venture yet.
   ---
   Steel prices are rising, leading some firms to restart
blast furnaces and to recall workers laid off last fall. The
rebound reflects brisk demand -- especially auto-related --
higher raw-material costs, and falling imports.
   ---
   Hitachi will unveil a mainframe computer this week far
more powerful than those on the market, boosting the Japanese
company's bid to become a major player in the U.S.
   ---
   Manville Corp. was ordered back to bankruptcy court by two
judges who urged changes in the funding and operation of a
trust that the company formed to pay asbestos claims.
   ---
   L.A. Gear disclosed it will post its first quarterly drop
in profit in three years. The news sent the sneaker maker's
stock plunging 22% to $30.75.
   ---
   Japan's current-account and overall trade surpluses
narrowed sharply in April. Tokyo is considering altering its
policy of reducing the surpluses.
   ---
   The failure of Western S&amp;L will add $1.7 billion to the
thrift-bailout cost, more than any other single rescue.
BankAmerica bought the Phoenix thrift's deposits, branches
and certain other assets for $81 million.
   ---
   Esprit's married founders settled their feud as Doug
Tompkins agreed to quit as image director and sell his 50%
stake in the apparel firm's U.S. operations to Susie
Tompkins.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 187,860,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2900.97, up 24.31; transportation 1189.42, up 17.89;
utilities 211.71, up 0.32.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3417.62, up
43.59.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.87, off 0.22;
spot index 133.34, off 0.46.
   Dollar: 151.85 yen, off 0.25; 1.6980 marks, up 0.0015.
</TEXT>
