<HL>
   Workplace (A Special Report): Where We'll Be
   ---
   Gearing Up:
   Here's a Primer on What You'll Need And
   What It Will Cost to Set Up Your Own Workplace
   ----
   By William M. Bulkeley
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE R12
</SO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Take a loathing for commuting and office life, combine it
with the electronics revolution, and what do you have? The
home-office boom.
   These days, an individual with a few thousand dollars'
worth of equipment can imitate a fully staffed law office,
accounting firm or engineering company. And the future
promises even lower prices -- and more sophisticated
machines.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Equipping a basic home office costs under $4,000, and even
a lavish setup is under $10,000. Here's a list of some of the
items that most home businesses are likely to buy today, with
prices culled from recent advertisements.
                                                                                                       

   Basic Needs
                                                                                                       

   IBM-compatible personal computer -- $1,000
   Prices have dropped sharply during most of the past six
months, and the most basic machines can be had for under
$500. But much of the best software today requires a hard
disk instead of cheaper floppy disks. The minimum computer
today should include an Intel 80286 processor, a 20-megabyte
hard disk and a monochrome monitor. Prices will keep dropping
30% a year.
                                                                                                       

   Letter-quality printer -- $270
   The 24-pin models print characters almost as well as
electric typewriters do.
                                                                                                       

   Answering machine -- $70
   After a telephone, the most important single item for any
home business.
                                                                                                       

   Facsimile machine -- $480
   The most basic models don't cut the paper or dial numbers
automatically, but they get the job done.
                                                                                                       

   Two-line telephone -- $120
   A must, unless you want to risk annoying clients with busy
signals or with constant requests to hold on while you answer
your call-waiting line.
                                                                                                       

   Computer modem -- $100
   The 2400-baud versions save lots of money when sending
electronic mail.
                                                                                                       

   High-Powered Office
                                                                                                       

   More powerful personal computers -- $3,099
   PCs with 100-megabyte hard disks will run faster and are
more likely to accommodate software packages that come out in
the future. Home workers say that the bigger the hard disk,
the better off you are.
   Hard-disk prices have been plunging lately. Color monitors
don't make much difference in the business, but they make the
kids' educational software look great -- and that's one of
the benefits of having a home office.
                                                                                                       

   Tape drive -- $380
   When all your business information is on your computer,
you need to back it up at least weekly. Keep the tape in the
car or elsewhere out of the house.
                                                                                                       

   Laser printers -- $995
   They let users print out headlines, different fonts, and
graphs and charts that look professionally produced. They are
almost silent and print at four to six pages a minute. Once
limited to print shops, they fell below $1,000 last fall.
                                                                                                       

   Personal copiers -- $530
   They're much less common in home offices than in corporate
offices. In emergencies, a fax machine can be used to make a
copy. And big jobs still require a trip to the print shop.
                                                                                                       

   Facsimile machine -- $800
   You might want one that includes an answering machine that
switches automatically to voice or fax.
                                                                                                       

   Software
                                                                                                       

   Buy a simple integrated package with word processing,
filing and spreadsheet built in; then add specialized
software as you find a need for it, advises Russ Walter,
author of "The Secret Guide to Computers." Unless you're
building a relationship with a computer retailer, buy
software by mail order. Join a user group for access to many
useful free programs. Some of the most popular software
includes:
                                                                                                       

   Integrated programs -- $100-$225
   Microsoft Works or Software Publishing's PFS First Choice.
Symantec's Q&amp;A is more expensive, but it combines easy but
sophisticated filing with adequate word processing.
                                                                                                       

   Word Processing -- $200-$300
   WordPerfect is the best seller. Microsoft Word, Samna's
Ami and Xyquest's Xywrite all have their fans.
                                                                                                       

   Spreadsheets -- $250-$330
   Lotus 1-2-3 version 2.2 is the best seller; many recent
reviewers prefer Borland's Quattro Pro and Microsoft's Excel.
                                                                                                       

   Accounting -- $35
   Intuit's Quicken, the best-selling check-writing program,
is easier than double-entry bookkeeping.
                                                                                                       

   Telecommunications
                                                                                                       

   Keeping a residential phone rate typically saves $5 a
month or so, but it keeps you out of the Yellow Pages. Some
telephone companies have special marketing plans for
home-based businesses. Experts recommend at least two lines,
one of which is hooked to the fax machine. Following are
monthly rates:
                                                                                                       

   Two lines, residential rates -- $20-$30
                                                                                                       

   Call waiting -- $5
                                                                                                       

   Voice mail boxes -- $6
   Just becoming available. The phone company will store
messages even if your line is busy, reducing the need for
another line and eliminating the need for call waiting.
                                                                                                       

   800 Number -- $20
   Lets distant customers call you at your expense. Be
careful about giving out the number because you get billed
for the incoming calls.
                                                                                                       

   MCI mail box -- $25 annual
   Lets people send and receive computerized messages.
                                                                                                       

   On the Road
                                                                                                       

   Without secretaries or assistants sitting in the office,
the home-based business person is even more dependent on
electronic lifelines while traveling.
                                                                                                       

   Cellular car phone -- $500
                                                                                                       

   Pocket cellular phone -- $1,200
                                                                                                       

   Portable computer -- $600-$4,000
   You pay for portability and screen quality.
                                                                                                       

   Portable facsimile machine -- $1,700
   Remember, it uses thermal paper, which will turn black
while sitting in a hot car.
                                                                                                       

   Portable printer -- $360
   ---
   Mr. Bulkeley is a staff reporter in The Wall Street
Journal's Boston bureau.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0052
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0052.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH AND GORBACHEV ENDED a four-day summit at odds over
Germany.
   Despite proclaiming that they had achieved "an atmosphere
of growing trust" during their talks in Washington, the
president and the Soviet leader concluded their talks amid
unresolved differences over the future military status of a
united Germany and on independence for the breakaway Baltic
republic of Lithuania. Still, the two leaders decided to meet
on a regular basis, perhaps annually, and Gorbachev invited
Bush to Moscow. They also signed a U.S.-Soviet trade pact
Friday, and reached accords to halt the production of
chemical weapons and on verification procedures for
nuclear-arms testing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev traveled to Minnesota for a brief visit with
political, business and agricultural officials before heading
to San Francisco for a meeting today with South Korea's
President Roh.
   ---
   Beijing University students hurled bricks and bottles at
China's security forces, and then staged an anti-government
rally on campus. The protest, on the anniversary of last
year's crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, was
considered the strongest since the government's assault in
Tiananmen Square and came amid tight security.
                                                                                                       

   Tens of thousands of people marked last year's Chinese
army attack on student-led protesters with demonstrations in
Hong Kong and elsewhere. Police estimated 100,000 people
joined in the Hong Kong march, considered the biggest rally
in the British colony since last summer's gathering in
support of China's pro-democracy movement.
   ---
   Genentech Inc. scientists conducted a test that protected
two chimpanzees from the AIDS virus. The company said
researchers vaccinated the animals with a copy of the virus's
outer coat, and then exposed them to the AIDS virus. After
more than six months, the chimps haven't shown signs of
infection.
   ---
   Dozens of Liberia's soldiers fled Monrovia, heading to
neighboring Sierra Leone amid fears of an expected rebel
attack aimed at overthrowing the government of President Doe.
Others evacuated their families, and residents of the capital
complained of food shortages. Troops on the battlefront
reportedly were retreating toward the city.
   ---
   A band of tornadoes struck the Midwest, killing at least
eight people and injuring about 150 in Indiana, where the
governor declared a state of emergency and dispatched the
National Guard to areas hardest hit by the twisters. At least
one person was killed in Illinois, officials said. The storms
reportedly left 24 cities with significant damage.
   ---
   Washington's Mayor Barry is scheduled to go on trial today
on cocaine conspiracy and perjury charges. But sources said
the 54-year-old official's defense attorneys met with
prosecutors over the weekend to discuss a possible plea
bargain. Barry was arrested Jan. 18 in an FBI sting
operation.
   ---
   Canada's Mulroney held emergency talks in Ottawa with the
country's 10 provincial premiers in an attempt to break a
constitutional impasse over granting French-speaking Quebec
special status. Three of the provinces oppose the move, part
of an accord that must be ratified by June 23.
   ---
   Mandela prepared for today's start of a six-week foreign
tour that includes stops throughout Africa, Europe and North
America. The African National Congress leader, who met
Saturday in Cape Town with de Klerk, is expected to try to
undo gains made by the South African president on an
eight-nation trip to Europe last month.
   ---
   Bulgaria barred soldiers from carrying arms outside
barracks after an officer killed an opposition activist two
weeks before the country's first free elections in four
decades. The Defense Ministry also ordered military officers
to surrender their personal weapons until June 17, the final
day of voting.
   ---
   Rival Cambodian officials said they expect to sign a
cease-fire agreement in Tokyo this week. But Prime Minister
Hun Sen of the Vietnam-backed Phnom Penh government and
Prince Sihanouk, head of a three-party guerrilla coalition,
cited differences over the role of the Khmer Rouge, which
could hinder the two-year peace process.
   ---
   Israel's Likud ministers reiterated a pledge to form a
narrow right-wing government by the end of the week. The
announcement, made after a strategy meeting called by
caretaker Prime Minister Shamir, followed a statement by
former Defense Minister Sharon, who said he would try to form
a hard-line coalition if Shamir failed.
   ---
   Died: Rex Harrison, 82, English-born actor whose career on
stage and film included portrayals of Henry Higgins in "My
Fair Lady," Saturday, in New York, of pancreatic cancer. . .
. Robert Noyce, 62, co-inventor of the semiconductor who was
a founder of Intel Corp. and president of the
government-industry consortium Sematech, in Austin, Texas, of
a heart attack. . . . Frederick Mellinger, 76, founder and
former chairman of Frederick's of Hollywood, Saturday, in Los
Angeles, of pneumonia. . . . Richard William Millar, 92,
former chairman of Northrop Corp., Friday, in Pasadena,
Calif.
</TEXT>
