<HL>
   Intermark Inc. Loss
   Widened to $14 Million
   In Fiscal 4th Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9C
</SO>
<CO>
   IMI
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. -- Intermark Inc.'s fiscal fourth-quarter
loss widened to $14 million, or $1.54 a share, from $7.2
million, or 79 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue in the period ended March 31 rose 69% to $277.7
million from $164.7 million, mainly reflecting the
consolidation of Intermark's results with those of Triton
Group Ltd. Intermark owns 52% of Triton's stock, and the two
firms recently agreed to merge, pending various approvals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Intermark had operating profit, before interest expense,
minority interest and taxes, of $4.7 million. A year earlier,
it posted a $14.6 million operating loss, including a $16
million provision for store closings at its Sunbelt Nursery
Group Inc. unit.
   Intermark said interest expense climbed to $14.1 million,
including $6.4 million from Triton, compared with $8.2
million a year earlier. The quarter also included a $4.3
million loss attributable to Munson Sporting Goods Co.
Intermark sold its stake in the wholesale sporting goods
distributor in February.
   For the year, Intermark posted a net loss of $10.7
million, or $1.20 a share, compared with net income of
$215,000, or one cent a share, in fiscal 1989. Revenue grew
39% to $945.5 million from $681.9 million. Operating profit
rose 21% to $47.3 million from $39.1 million.
   Intermark and Triton holds interests in numerous operating
companies in retailing, restaurants, real estate and other
industries. Intermark said the strongest operating
performances in fiscal 1990 were from Sunbelt Nursery, which
contributed $10 million of profit in contrast to a $22
million loss the year before, and from Pier 1 Imports Inc.,
whose contribution jumped by 12% to $48 million.
   "While the fiscal year 1990 loss is disappointing, we feel
good about the progress made by our partner companies during
the year and about the general health of our business," said
Charles R. Scott, Intermark chairman and chief executive
officer. "The growth in operating income during 1990 is a
clear indication of the strength of our companies."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0012
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0012.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   NCNB Acquires
   Most Remnants
   Of Texas Firm
   ----
   By Martha Brannigan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   NCB NBCTC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. -- NCNB Corp. acquired most of the
remnants of the failed National Bancshares Corp. of Texas,
based in San Antonio, increasing its stake in the state by
purchasing $1 billion in assets and assuming $1.5 billion in
liabilities.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. approved NCNB's
proposal to assume the deposits and secured liabilities of
nine of the 12 bank subsidiaries of National Bancshares. The
banks are expected to reopen today as units of NCNB Texas
National Banking Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Since its entry into Texas in 1988, the ever-aggressive
NCNB has grown to be the largest bank in the state by picking
up sundry pieces from the Texas banking disaster. With this
acquisition, NCNB Texas will have $31.4 billion in assets and
250 branches in 77 communities.
   In a statement, Kenneth D. Lewis, president of NCNB Texas,
called the transaction "a major step in NCNB's expansion
strategy and an excellent addition to our trust business." He
said it doubles the number of locations in San Antonio, which
NCNB considers an attractive market, and gives NCNB a
presence in seven new communities. The FDIC said the nine
bank units are based in Austin, Boerne, Corpus Christi,
Houston, Kerrville, Mission, San Antonio, Sequin and Uvalde.
   Under terms of the transaction, the FDIC will infuse
$581.2 million into the assuming bank and will retain assets
of the failed banks with a book value of $613.7 million, the
agency said. NCNB agreed to pay a premium of $59.5 million
for the $1.5 billion in deposits it is assuming.
   Until the end of April, it appeared that National
Bancshares would be acquired by Equimark Corp., the
Pittsburgh bank holding company. Under a recapitalization
plan drafted in mid-1989, Equimark agreed to invest or raise
about $116 million of new capital for National Bancshares. At
the same time, the FDIC was expected to invest about $250
million to eliminate the negative net worth -- assets minus
liabilities -- of subsidiary banks and cover losses from
problem assets.
   In late April, however, the FDIC unexpectedly scuttled the
plan rather than bow to bondholders' demands that it sweeten
its offer. Some banking industry observers also speculated
that the recapitalization failure owed as much to Equimark's
problems at home as it did to recalcitrant bondholders.
Buffeted by the weak commercial real-estate market, Equimark
had a $15.4 million loss in the first quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
