<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Suzie Wong Revisited
   ----
   By William McGurn
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   It was the late 1950s, it was the Wanchai district of Hong
Kong, and a Chinese bar girl was explaining to a tall,
puzzled American that she could not possibly be the nice girl
he'd met earlier in the day. "What a nice girl you met on
ferry doing in a place like this I like to know for goodness
sake," she tells him, ending with her favorite expression.
Her name, of course, was Suzie Wong, and the part would
launch an unknown 21-year-old named Nancy Kwan into stardom.
   Three decades after she first shimmied across the screen
and into William Holden's grudging heart, Ms. Kwan still
looks young enough to catch a sailor's eye -- a testament no
doubt to the Oriental Pearl Cream she now hawks on late-night
TV.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Shortly after "The World of Suzie Wong," she put her Royal
Ballet training to good use as the scheming nightclub
performer Linda Low in Rodgers and Hammerstein's "Flower Drum
Song." Like the good-hearted Suzie, Linda was somewhat
pre-Betty Friedan in her outlook ("It's nice to have outside
accomplishments . . . but the main thing is for a woman to be
successful in her gender"); she sings the film's big song, "I
Enjoy Being a Girl."
   Ms. Kwan has gone on to prove herself decidedly more
diverse, having branched out into producing and writing in
addition to acting. But she too enjoys what life's given her
and thus has little time for modern complaints that the
cheongsam she wore as Suzie Wong -- the traditional
tightfitting, high-collared, Chinese slit sheath -- was
exploitative.
   "I still think it's very feminine," she says, conceding,
however, that "if you don't have the right figure, it
accentuates all the wrong places."
   Today home for Ms. Kwan is a modest ranch house tucked
away in Sherman Oaks, Calif., far removed from the hustle and
bustle of her native Hong Kong but filled with more Chinese
pieces than the emperor's palace. Toward "The World of Suzie
Wong" she exhibits a healthy indifference tinged with
appreciation for the opportunity. It was, she says, "just a
job," and indeed she tried out for the part on a lark only
after director Ray Stark spied her hanging around her uncle's
film studio during a school holiday from Britain. Of co-star
William Holden, she has only praise for an actor who was
"exceptionally generous" with others. "He was a man's man and
a woman's man if you know what I mean," she says. Her
Cantonese upbringing compels her to add that he "was a good
businessman, too."
   For though born of an English mother and now carrying an
American passport, Ms. Kwan was raised a daughter of the
Celestial Kingdom. Her Chinese name is Kwan Ka Shen, from a
family that traces itself back to Kwan Kung, a general so
renowned for his uprightness that his red-faced visage adorns
many a police station and shop. She relates how, as a young
student, she had intended to join a demonstration against one
of the many British-run Hong Kong clubs that wouldn't allow
Chinese as members. Her father, a famous local architect,
asked her not to, and out of filial piety, she did what any
Chinese girl would have done. She obeyed.
   Not long after "The World of Suzie Wong" made her a star
she left Hong Kong for work reasons but returned in the 1970s
to start up a production company called Nancy Kwan Films. In
the interim she's also kept up her acting career, appearing
in everything from the pilot for the old TV series "Hawaii
Five-O" to "Miracle Landing," the recent CBS docudrama about
the 1988 Aloha Airlines flight that survived losing its roof
in midair.
   It's been three years now since Ms. Kwan's visited Hong
Kong, but she eagerly quizzes a former resident about
prospects come the 1997 transfer of sovereignty from London
to Beijing. Like most Chinese, she is glad to see the end of
colonial rule; like most Hong Kong Chinese, she has her
worries. "I am Chinese and Hong Kong people are Chinese," she
says, fingering a jade bracelet. "Nevertheless, I wouldn't
like to see its special identity swallowed up by China."
   These days, however, her ethnic pride takes the
characteristically American form of volunteer work for such
organizations as the Association of Asian Pacific American
Artists. Things have changed considerably since the days when
Caucasians played Charlie Chan, but the organization remains
concerned about the public image of Asians. She also works on
behalf of the Vietnamese boat people, as well as heading up
public liaison for the Asian American Voters Coalition.
Although Asian Americans treasure the freedoms that have
enabled them to prosper in their new home, Ms. Kwan notes
that they have been reluctant to get involved in politics
because they by and large come from "police states where
politics get you in trouble." She reports proudly that the
White House requested a copy of her speech to an October AAVC
conference in Washington.
   For similar reasons she also is pleased about her upcoming
part in Frank Vinh Noan's "Endless Love." The story revolves
around an American separated from her Vietnamese husband and
infant daughter by the fall of Saigon, and Ms. Kwan plays the
Chinese-Vietnamese U.N. official fighting to bring them back
together. In the process she falls in love with a well-known
anti-war reporter now feeling some guilt pangs about the
consequences of the American defeat there. What makes this
film different from the dozens of others about Vietnam is
that this is the first seen through the eyes of a Vietnamese.
In addition to landing one of the lead roles, Ms. Kwan will
be co-producing the project, to be shot this summer, probably
in Thailand.
   Too soon the interview winds down, and it comes time to
ask for an autograph. Admitting to some wariness about the
press ("words never seem to turn out the way I said them"),
she nonetheless takes pen in hand and bends over a photo, a
formal portrait of her grandfather dressed in his imperial
robes. "A word is worth a thousand pictures," she writes, and
a reporter suggests that while flattering it's probably
untrue. The observation draws a mischevious smile. "Of course
it's not true," she says.
   For goodness sake.
   ---
   Mr. McGurn is Washington bureau chief of the National
Review.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0009
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0009.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Baseball-Card Marketer Fleer Corp.
   Is Offering an 18.5% Stake to Public
   ----
   By Neal Lipschutz
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9D
</SO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Investors are about to get another opportunity
to join in the baseball card craze without having to worry
about such things as how to value a Mickey Mantle rookie
card.
   Fleer Corp., which describes itself as the third biggest
of six national marketers of sports cards, plans an initial
offering this week of 1.7 million common shares, representing
an 18.5% stake.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In one sign of investor interest, lead underwriter Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. has been talking about an issue
price of $13 to $15 a share, rather than the $11 to $13
originally expected.
   And even at $13 to $15, the issue would be fairly priced,
says Al Hadhazy, senior analyst for the newsletter New
Issues. There could be more attractive initial public
offerings in the pipeline, he says, but Fleer has strong
fundamentals including a tripling of annual sales between
1986 and 1989.
   "I like the stock," says Robert Natale, an analyst who
tracks new issues at Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. At $13 to $15 a
share, he says, the stock would be "less attractive but still
{would have} appeal."
   As interest in baseball cards and other sports
collectibles has boomed, so have Fleer's sales, especially of
its baseball cards packaged with team stickers. On a pro
forma basis, revenue last year was $83.4 million, and net
income was $6.9 million.
   In this year's first quarter, the company's pro forma net
was $6.8 million, or 74 cents a share, compared with $2
million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier. Sales climbed
to $40.2 million from $20.6 million.
   The company says in its preliminary prospectus that a
"substantial majority" of its revenue and earnings are
generated in the first half of the year from baseball card
sales.
   Meanwhile, the leading baseball card concern, Topps Co.,
had record sales and net in its year ended March 3. Net was
$37.6 million, or $1.20 a share, on sales of $246.4 million,
after fiscal 1989 net of $28 million, or 89 cents a share, on
sales of $198.8 million.
   A Topps spokesman said he couldn't estimate the company's
share of the baseball card market. In calling itself the No.
3 company, Fleer says in its preliminary prospectus that "the
current market leader has a significantly larger share of the
market for baseball cards than any other entity."
   If the increased interest in baseball card collecting
continues, competition is sure to heat up further, says Mr.
Hadhazy of the New Issues letter. "Any number of companies
can jump into the ball game at any time," he says, and he
doesn't expect Fleer to maintain its growth rate of the past
four years.
   And what if enthusiasm for the cards wanes? Fleer
acknowledges that its sales can be "significantly impacted by
changing consumer tastes and interests."
   Mr. Hadhazy says, "I wouldn't say I'm ready to call it a
fad, but in terms of speculative frenzy, baseball cards are
right up there."
   However, Mr. Natale of S&amp;P says, "It's a faddish business,
but it's also a perennial one." Collectors aren't the only
purchasers of the cards, he points out. Fleer, in fact, says
its primary market is "the young consumer, aged six to 16."
   Fleer markets its baseball and other sports cards under
non-exclusive license agreements with players' associations
and representatives of leagues and teams.
   Fleer says in the preliminary prospectus, "Although there
can be no assurance that new licenses will be granted . . .
the company anticipates that it will obtain new licenses on
terms acceptable to it." Future licenses, however, could be
granted to other companies, and analysts say it's possible
that sports leagues or player groups might eventually decide
to market the cards themselves.
   Fleer began selling baseball cards in 1981. It introduced
basketball cards in 1986 and expects to begin marketing
football cards this summer. The company also makes bubble
gum, mostly marketed under the Dubble Bubble brand, as well
as Razzles, a gum product pressed into the form of a tablet.
   An investment group led by Charterhouse Equity Partners
acquired Fleer last August through a holding company, Charter
Confectionary Inc., for $55.4 million. Charter Confectionary
was merged into Fleer in April of this year. The company says
it doesn't have any current plan to begin paying dividends.
Proceeds from the stock sale will be used to reduce debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900604-0008
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900604-0008.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Synchrotron Facility
   Construction Begins
   By Energy Agency
</HL>
<DATE>
06/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7F
</SO>
<GV>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)
</GV>
<LP>
   ARGONNE, Ill. -- The Department of Energy's Argonne
National Laboratory is scheduled to break ground today for
the $456 million Advanced Photon Source, a device that will
generate X-ray beams 10,000 times brighter than those from
any existing source.
   The new-generation synchrotron, an aluminum circle
two-thirds of a mile in length, will succeed DOE's Brookhaven
National Laboratory on Long Island as the world's most
powerful X-ray source.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Synchrotrons, originally developed for particle research,
produce powerful X-rays as a by-product of accelerating
electrons through magnetic fields. Scientists can use such
rays to determine the precise positions of atoms in chemical
reactions.
   The Argonne device will produce X-rays with higher
energies: There are "more photons, or light particles, in the
beam so you get data faster," said a lab spokesman.
Scientists will be able to "do experiments at APS in a few
hours that would require months at Brookhaven," he added.
   Experiments at the Argonne lab aren't scheduled to get
under way until 1996, however, by which time a slightly less
powerful machine now under construction in Europe will be
operational, and another device in Japan will also be
starting up.
   Argonne is operated by the University of Chicago for the
DOE.
   The lab says the APS will be "fundamentally for basic
research." The spokesman, however, stressed that it is
"research that's expected to produce lots of practical
results," in fields such as computer science, ceramics,
chemistry and physics.
   Argonne said scientists from companies including
Allied-Signal Inc., Exxon Corp., International Business
Machines Corp., and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s Bell
Laboratories have helped plan and design the facility, and
have indicated interest in using the facility when it's
completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
